<HEADLINE>
<P>
SOCKERS OPEN OCT. 28; ALL-STAR GAME HERE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICK HAZELTINE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The defending champion Sockers will play at Dallas on Oct. 28 to open the 
1989-90 Major Indoor Soccer League season and then play Kansas City Nov. 3 in 
their home opener at the Sports Arena. 
</P>
<P>
The schedule, released by the MISL Tuesday, includes a bonus: The MISL All-Star 
game will be played at the Sports Arena Feb. 21. 
</P>
<P>
With the addition of the St. Louis Storm and Cleveland Crunch, the MISL also 
split the league back into two divisions after a year without them. The Western 
Division includes the Sockers, Storm, Dallas Sidekicks and Tacoma Stars, and 
Eastern Division the Crunch, Baltimore Blast, Kansas City Comets and Wichita 
Wings. 
</P>
<P>
The Sockers' schedule includes four more games (52) than last season. All but 
four of their 26 home dates will be Friday, Saturday or Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
The team also will play 13 pairs of games on consecutive nights. 
</P>
<P>
The MISL playoffs will include the top three teams from each division, with the 
division champion receiving a first-round bye. The No. 2 and 3 teams in each 
division will play a best-of-five series (two games at one site, two at the 
other, returning to the first site for the final game, if necessary). The 
winners will then play the division champions in a seven-game, two-three-two 
series, to be followed by another series with the same format for the 
championship. 
</P>
<P>
The Sockers also formally announced the signing of Waad Hirmez, the ninth 
player to sign for the 1989-90 season. Hirmez, who started last season with the 
Los Angeles Lazers, has a one-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
Hirmez, who played at Point Loma High School, returned to the Sockers last 
season in a trade that sent Poli Garcia to Los Angeles. Hirmez scored 26 goals 
and added 18 assists in 46 games last season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
