<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: TV &amp; VIDEO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALEENE MacMINN, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Well, so much for the critics," NBC News president Michael Gartner scoffs in a 
staff memo noting the ratings success of "Yesterday, Today and Tomorrow," which 
critics roasted because of its news re-creations. "The viewers viewed -- in big 
numbers," the news chief crows in his communique. He said "YTT" won its time 
slot with a 12 rating and 23% audience share and held "its audience throughout 
the hour" for its debut last Wednesday at 10 p.m. He also noted that the debut 
of ABC's far more publicized "PrimeTime Live" last Thursday "had lesser numbers 
and was third in its time period." Two more editions of "YTT" will air on Aug. 
23 and Sept. 13, after which NBC will decide if the program will go as a 
series. ALEENE MacMINN 
</P>
