<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: TV &amp; VIDEO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALEENE MacMINN, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"thirtysomething," noted for occasionally flouting TV dramatic conventions with 
dream sequences and offbeat fantasy episodes, may break the mold again next 
season with a live episode, producers Marshall Herskovitz and Ed Zwick said 
Tuesday. Although they would not reveal the plot, Herskovitz said, "So much of 
what we do in our show is to interpret reality for people. The notion of doing 
something live . . . gives us certain opportunities you can't get on film." The 
episode would air live on the East Coast and be seen on tape delay here in the 
West. ALEENE MacMINN 
