<P>
PRO-CHOICE GOP CANDIDATE HOLDS LEAD IN 76TH ASSEMBLY DISTRICT VOTE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire service reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The only pro-choice candidate in a field of six Republicans held a 212-vote 
lead today with 700 absentee ballots yet to be counted in a special primary 
election to fill an Assembly seat in a conservative Southern California 
district. 
</P>
<P>
If Tricia Hunter, a registered nurse from Bonita, holds onto her lead after the 
absentee ballots are counted, she will face pro-choice Democrat Jeannine 
Correia of Poway in an Oct. 3 runoff in the heavily Republican 76th District 
that covers arid sections of San Diego and Riverside counties. 
</P>
<P>
The campaign attracted national attention as the first test of strength for 
pro-choice and anti-abortion forces since a U.S. Supreme Court ruling July 3 
giving state legislatures more power to regulate abortion. 
